AI for Health – Breathing Irregularity Detection

About Me
Myself Lalitha Janneti, and I am currently a B.Tech second year student  in Computer Science and Engineering. I am interested in Machine Learning, Artificial Intelligence, and solving real-world problems using data.
Through this project, I aimed to understand how physiological signals can be used to detect health-related conditions. I wanted to gain hands-on experience in signal processing, dataset preparation, and deep learning model implementation.
This project helped me combine theoretical knowledge with practical implementation in the healthcare domain.
1. What This Project Is About
In this project, I worked on detecting abnormal breathing patterns during sleep. The goal was to identify breathing problems such as apnea and hypopnea using physiological signals collected overnight from participants.
The dataset contained 8 hours of sleep data for each participant. My task was to process the signals, prepare the dataset, build a model, and evaluate its performance.
2. What I Learned
Through this project, I learned:
    • How to handle real biomedical time-series data
    • How to clean messy raw text files
    • How to apply signal processing techniques
    • How to split continuous signals into windows
    • How to label windows using event overlap
    • How to handle different sampling rates
    • How to build a 1D CNN model for time-series classification
    • How to evaluate models using proper cross-validation
This project helped me understand both signal processing and deep learning together.
3. Understanding the Data
Each participant had the following signals:
    • Nasal Airflow (32 Hz)
    • Thoracic Movement (32 Hz)
    • SpO₂ (4 Hz)
    • Event file containing abnormal breathing intervals
The signals were long time-series data collected over 8 hours.
Before building a model, I first visualized the signals to understand their behavior. I plotted airflow, thoracic movement, and oxygen levels, and highlighted breathing events on the graphs.
This helped me clearly see how abnormal breathing affects airflow and oxygen saturation.
4. Signal Processing
Normal breathing usually occurs between 10 and 24 breaths per minute. This corresponds to a frequency range of 0.17 Hz to 0.4 Hz.
To remove noise and keep only relevant breathing information, I applied a bandpass filter between 0.17 Hz and 0.4 Hz to:
    • Nasal airflow
    • Thoracic movement
This helped in keeping only meaningful breathing patterns and removing unwanted signal noise.
5. Creating the Dataset
Sleep studies usually analyze data in 30-second intervals. So I divided the signals into:
    • 30-second windows
    • 50% overlap between windows
The overlap increases the number of samples and helps capture transitions between breathing states.
For labeling:
    • If a window overlapped more than 50% with an annotated breathing event, I labeled it with that event.
    • Otherwise, I labeled it as Normal.
This created a structured dataset where each window contains:
    • Airflow data
    • Thoracic movement data
    • SpO₂ data
    • Label
    • Participant ID
6. Handling Different Sampling Rates
Airflow and thoracic signals were sampled at 32 Hz, but SpO₂ was sampled at 4 Hz.
To combine all three signals into one model, I upsampled the SpO₂ signal so that all signals had the same time length per window.
This allowed the CNN model to process them together correctly.
7. Model Implementation
I built a 1D Convolutional Neural Network (1D CNN) to classify breathing patterns.
I chose 1D CNN because:
    • The data is time-series.
    • CNN can learn local patterns in breathing signals.
    • It works well for physiological signals.
The model takes three input channels:
    • Airflow
    • Thoracic movement
    • SpO₂
It outputs the predicted breathing class.
8. Evaluation Method
Instead of randomly splitting data, I used Leave-One-Participant-Out Cross Validation.
This means:
    • Train on 4 participants
    • Test on the remaining participant
    • Repeat for all 5 participants
This method ensures the model is tested on unseen participants and avoids overfitting to a specific person.
9. Results and Observations
The model was able to classify breathing patterns with reasonable accuracy.
Performance varied slightly between participants, which shows that breathing patterns differ between individuals.
Using Leave-One-Participant-Out validation helped ensure fair evaluation.
10. Challenges I Faced
    • Handling messy raw signal files
    • Parsing event annotation files correctly
    • Managing different sampling rates
    • Avoiding data leakage
    • Correctly calculating overlap for labeling
Solving these problems helped me improve my debugging and data processing skills.

